[Student "W"]
{You are East. The bidding has been as shown. You led the \SA, West plays the \S9, North the \S5. You assume West has signaled you to continue \Ss, so you play the \SQ. On this trick West plays the \S3 and North the \S8. How will you continue? 

You know that both West and North are now void of \Ss. You might just switch suits, but you have a better choice.

If you play your \SQ, West won't bother ruffing, North <b>WILL</b> ruff and dummy's \SJ will be established as a winner.

The best procedure is to lead a low \S. West will ruff and North will over-ruff but by playing this way you stop the establishment of South's \SJ. As you can see, North would have been able to discard a loser on that \SJ if you hadn't played this way.}
[Play "W"]SA

